04215nam a2200625Ia 9780292758957DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20131992txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927589577 a10.7560/7114882doi  a(DE-B1597)588264  a(OCoLC)1280944087  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPR6037.N58bZ62 1992eb 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a823/.9122201 ade la Mothe, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aC. P. Snow and the Struggle of Modernity /cJohn de la Mothe. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2013] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (263 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart One. Introduction -- t1 Literature, Science, and the Modern Mind -- tPart Two. Context and Distance -- t2 Strangers and Brothers against the Grain -- t3 Blindness, Insight, and the Two Cultures -- tPart Three. Snow's Triptych of Literature, Science, and Politics -- t4 Literature and the State of Siege -- t5 The Unneutrality of Science -- t6 Personal Power and Public Affairs -- tPart Four. Epilogue -- t7 C. P. Snow and the Struggle of Modernity -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe condition of modernity springs from that tension between science and the humanities that had its roots in the Enlightenment but reached its full flowering with the rise of twentieth-century technology. It manifests itself most notably in the crisis of individuality that is generated by the nexus of science, literature, and politics, one that challenges each of us to find a way of balancing our personal identities between our public and private selves in an otherwise estranging world. This challenge, which can only be expressed as "the struggle of modernity," perhaps finds no better expression than in C. P. Snow. In his career as novelist, scientist, and civil servant, C. P. Snow (1905-1980) attempted to bridge the disparate worlds of modern science and the humanities. While Snow is often regarded as a late-Victorian liberal who has little to say about the modernist period in which he lived and wrote, de la Mothe challenges this judgment, reassessing Snow's place in twentieth-century thought. He argues that Snow's life and writings—most notably his Strangers and Brothers sequence of novels and his provocative thesis in The Two Cultures and the Scientific Revolution—reflect a persistent struggle with the nature of modernity. They manifest Snow's belief that science and technology were at the center of modern life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCivil servicezGreat BritainvBiography. 0aNovelists, Englishy20th centuryvBiography. 0aScientistszGreat BritainvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71148840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292758957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292758957/original  a978-3-11-074535-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles